post_text:
As our seniors cross the stage tonight at McCauley Mountain separated from the community that has supported them through their entire school career we wanted to make sure you could see the members of the Town of Webb UFSD Class of 2020 in this graduation ceremony video. The video was compiled from two days of intimate half hour graduations in the gymnasium last week. The graduates and their families got to celebrate together and document this milestone in ways that wouldn't have happened had we not had to rethink how to do graduation during this pandemic. We hope you enjoy this video that Travis Kiefer put together for our graduates uniting their independent experiences together as a cohesive and fitting celebration of this unique year.
https://drive.google.com/file/d/1d7V78wNp9TCJkXkoBvXPl7rL0kWhwxC-/view?usp=sharing
Congratulations Graduates! We wish you all the best in all that you endeavor to accomplish in the future. Stay well and be kind!

Tonight we celebrate our graduates together (but socially distanced) at McCauley Mountain. Graduates and their families will begin their final school graduation event by processing through town from Enchanted Forest by school and turning by the post office on their way to McCauley Mountain. This procession is scheduled to leave EFWS at 6:30PM tonight with the graduation beginning at 7PM. Due to COVID restrictions the event at McCauley is a closed event and the general public unfortunately can not be in attendance to support our graduating class in person.
Cheer them on from a distance and watch the videos that will post later tonight to see The Town of Webb UFSD Class of 2020 graduate!
Congratulations to our graduates and their families!!

The 2020 yearbooks have arrived. If you ordered one it should be delivered on Monday with the meal deliveries and device/book collection. We have a very limited number of books remaining if you would like to purchase one please contact Mrs. Amos before they are gone. They are $40 each and you can contact her via email at damos@towschool.org. Mrs. Amos and her Yearbook Students did a great job on them this year!

Seniors received their books yesterday and had a virtual meeting yesterday afternoon to surprise our nurse, Mrs. Katie Boesche with their dedication of the book to her this year. Mrs. Boesche is retiring at the end of the year and we all thank her for her time with our students taking care of all of their needs.

Congratulations Nurse Boesche and best wishes for a wonderful retirement!

post_text:
On June 8th Governor Cuomo issued Executive Order 202.39 extending the deadline for school districts to receive school budget and BOE election ballots through 5pm on June 16th. After 5pm June 9th ballots will only be counted if received by mail. All ballots must follow absentee guidelines and be sealed in the absentee ballot envelope. Please remember to sign the ballot envelope in order to be valid.
Per executive order, all ballots received after 5pm on June 9 must be via United States Postal Service and may not be hand-delivered.

Spring Awards are on the calendar for tomorrow (Wednesday, June 3rd). This Spring has not been anything we anticipated but we will still be recognizing our students both academically and athletically.
We will post a link to the virtual (recorded) awards night tomorrow for everyone to view and applaud our students and their accomplishments even though we are apart. There is a wonderful keynote speaker and the coaches have recorded their messages to our students as well. The academic awards were finalized today and will also be announced as part of this online presentation. The actual awards will be on their way to our students on Thursday (as long as the suppliers have been able to produce them during the closures).
Check back tomorrow! This is an event that COVID didn’t cancel!

If you haven't checked the email you use for school contact in the last 24 hours please do so. An email was sent out yesterday outlining how your classes will be handled for the 4th quarter. The mandated school closure will continue according to Governor Cuomo's executive orders and teachers will continue to provide work for you to complete with their help and guidance at home.

He stated: "If you can't maintain social distancing you have to wear a mask."
He further stated that this order will go into effect on Friday, April 17th. Situations where this is important are when you go to the grocery store, pharmacy, post office or even when walking alone if you might come into contact with others also walking on the sidewalk.
Stay well!

post_text:
We hope you are all doing well during this unusual and challenging time. Remember if you need anything you can reach out to us for help. Please call 315-244-7748 if you need anything.
If you are currently participating in our meal program we wanted to let you know that the program will continue until the end of the Governor's mandatory school closure. This includes the time currently scheduled for Spring Recess. If your needs have changed and you need to sign up for food deliveries please email or call Mrs. Rouse in the cafeteria to get added to the list for deliveries on Mondays and Thursdays. You can email her at krouse@towschool.org or call the main line and use the prompts to get to the cafeteria. Please note that office phones are not being answered at this time due to staffing restrictions.
If you have a change in need and no longer need meals please also let the cafeteria know so that they can plan accordingly and not waste meals.
Stay well. Keep your mind and body busy and engaged. Socially distance and stay home to help minimize the spread.
We miss you!

post_text:
Create a schedule and don't be overwhelmed. Our teachers are doing a great job getting work to you but it doesn't have to be done all at once. Take breaks just like you would in school. Take time to move. Take time to rest. Take snack breaks. Take time to explore within the learning opportunities provided to inspire new thoughts and ideas. Allow yourself/your students freedoms that will keep them nourished and inspired in the absence of their teachers standing next to them. Take time to be active/play and take time to clear your head and just be calm. It will all be ok.
If you have any needs from food to child care to mental health needs please reach out to us so we can help or find you an agency that can.
Included in this post is one of many sample schedules that can be found to help structure the day for your students (and the new teachers at home). The age level of your student(s) can drastically change the schedule and the time that should be spent on academic work vs creative play time.

Resilient students display social competence, problem-solving skills, personal responsibility and a sense of purpose and future. Students learn to choose conflict resolution over conflict and respect for others over disrespect."

We would like to thank Catholic Charities, VIEW and Great Pines for helping to bring this important work to our students today in an effort to impact the future for all.

COVID-19 (Coronavirus)
We are receiving daily updates at this point from both the State Education Department/State Health Department and the CDC. As of yesterday morning there are two confirmed cases of the virus in New York and the expectation is that those numbers will only increase.
The FLU continues to impact our students during this time of heightened viral awareness as well so it is best to remind everyone that the most important thing we can be doing to protect ourselves is to have good and frequent handwashing habits. Singing Happy Birthday while scrubbing your hands with soap and water has always been a great method to ensure you are washing thoroughly. Please be the role models at home and speak to your children about what good hand washing looks like and how important it is.
As we continue to get information we will be sure to share it with you from the perspective of the school community so that we can help each other all remain healthy.

https://www.cdc.gov/handwashing/index.html

Lyme 62

The eskimos went up 53-50 with 7 seconds left then Kyle Gaumes from Lyme hit a 3 at the buzzer to send the game into overtime. With both Jimmy and Roman fouled out the other Eskimos fought hard but it wasn't enough. Give credit to the Indians as they never gave up and pulled out the victory. Their coaches and players were respectful and we wish them luck moving forward.

shared_text:
Old Forge Boys Varsity Basketball is at Town of Webb UFSD.
February 25 at 10:12 PM · Old Forge, NY ·

Faith Heritage 64
Old Forge 67

Eskimos down 8 at the half came out in the 3rd on a 10-0 run showing such incredible fight. Jimmy Connell scored his 1000th point during that run and scored 21 2nd half points finishing with 26 points. Up 55-53, Roman McGrady missed the front end of a 1 and 1, Aiden Retzos took the ball the full length of the court and got fouled with .5 seconds left. He hit both free throws to send the game into overtime. Sasha Fielteau fouled out and wasnt available in overtime but the rest of the Eskimos stepped up for the win. Calvin Barkauskas and Sasha Fielteau combined for 16 points all while keeping their 2 stars Aiden Retzos and Shahad Sullivan in check. The McGrady boys again controlled the tempo, combined for 25 points and made some big buckets down the stretch. Ethan Ehrensbeck with 7 huge rebounds. The Eskimos move on to OCC Saturday.

Jimmy Connell 26pts-15rebs-5blocks

Roman McGrady 17pts-8rebs-5assists

Sasha Fielteau 9pts-10rebs

Roger McGrady 8pts-5rebs

Calvin Barkauskas 7pts-3rebs

Ethan Ehrensbeck 7rebs

The Polar Bear Ski Club would like to wish the Town of Webb Alpine and Nordic Ski Teams Good Luck at States this week! The teams will be attending NYSPHSAA Skiing Championships at Bristol Mountain. Old Forge Boys Varsity Basketball is at Town of Webb UFSD.
February 23 at 12:39 PM · Old Forge, NY ·

Sectional Quarterfinals

Tuesday 7pm

#15 Faith Heritage Saints (15-6) vs. #20 Old Forge Eskimos (16-5)

The 6 seeded Saints coming from Syracuse out of the OHSL Patriot American League made up of mostly class C schools.

Faith Heritage is a private school featuring 2 Junior superstars in Aiden Retzos averaging 30.6ppg and Shahad Sullivan averaging 17.1ppg. Retzos put up 48 points and Sullivan had 30 in Faith's first round matchup against 11th seeded Madison. Faith won 84-73. Old Forge won their first round game vs Remsen 61-49.

The winner will move on to the section semifinals Saturday at Onondaga Community College to play the winner of 2 seeded Lyme and 7 seeded McGraw.

Please do your best to stay positive in the stands on Tuesday, thank you and we appreciate your support.

***$3 admission fee per Section 3***

February 21 at 10:21 PM · Old Forge, NY ·

Remsen 49
Old Forge 61

Remsen showed up and stormed out to a 7 point halftime lead but the Eskimos rallied to outscore the Rams 39-20 in the 2nd half. With Seniors Jimmy Connell and Sasha Fielteau in foul trouble the rest of the team stepped up. Senior Calvin Barkauskas played arguably his best game of his career throughout the game and the McGrady brothers picked up their team scoring 35 points combined. shared_text:
Old Forge Boys Varsity Basketball is at Town of Webb UFSD.
February 17 at 10:09 PM · Old Forge, NY ·

Old Forge 63
New York Mills 52

With 4 Eskimos in double figures the eskimos used a total team effort to secure the CSC IV league title for the first time in 34 years and 5th time ever in school history. The McGrady boys controlled the tempo in a very tough environment at New York Mills. Jimmy Connell found his shot in the 2nd half scoring 14 2nd half points. Calvin Barkauskas playing sick, gave Old Forge just enough energy to contribute to the victory. Ethan Ehrensbeck and Nolan Fenton stepped in to give some much needed breaks for their teammates. Cliff Donovan, Cedric Barkauskas and Kevin Greco cheered from the bench.

In the best game of his career, Sasha Fielteau turned in 16pts and 11 rebs all while holding NYM star Logan Copperwheat to just 2 field goals the last 3 quarters after scoring 13 points in the first.

Jimmy Connell
17pts-10rebs

Sasha Fielteau
16pts-11rebs

Roman McGrady
13pts-9assists-6steals

Roger McGrady
11pts-5rebs

Calvin Barkauskas
6pts-5rebs

shared_text:
Old Forge Boys Varsity Basketball is at Town of Webb UFSD.
February 14 at 2:04 PM · Old Forge, NY ·

Old Forge at 8-1 in the league is a game ahead of Hamilton in the standings. With only 1 game left, Monday at New York Mills this means the Eskimos have clinched atleast a share of the CSC IV division league title. It is the first league title in 34 years and only the 5th in school history.

A win Monday secures a 3 seed in sectionals and clinches the league title outright.

Jimmy Connell is 35 points short of 1000 points for his career. He would be the first player to reach 1000 since Joe O'Donnell in 1995 who scored 1070.

Jimmy's mom Kathy Connell (Clark) is the schools leading scorer at 1099 points. Mike Gaffney is the only other 1000 point scorer from Old Forge with 1027 back in 1990.

Good luck to Jimmy and the rest of the Eskimos!!!!

Since we are living inside of a "Frozen" movie setting this morning...
Let it Glo, let it Glo let it Glo! AP Biology transformed bacteria with the pGlo gene, normally found in certain jellyfish. This gene allows the jellyfish to be bioluminescent, which can ward off predators. AP Bio students used biotechnology to insert this gene into bacteria, so now they glow under UV light!

post_text:
Skulls aren't just for Halloween! They are truly something to learn from.
Our science department has collaborated on scaling down and 3D printing models of hominid skulls that were scanned at museums around the world for a lab done in the AP Bio class. They are 58% scale due to the size constraints of our 3D printer. Science catalogs sell each of these skull models for $200-$300 so not only is printing them here a good experience it is also a money saver. This is also a great opportunity for our students to see and hold models of objects that are unique and only exist in vaults of museums around the world.

post_text:
As many already know one of our students was struck by a vehicle while riding his bicycle yesterday afternoon. Although he has some serious injuries we are hearing that he is stable and headed toward a good recovery. He is currently in Syracuse where he was flown after the accident yesterday and where he will remain for now.
Please keep your positive energy, thoughts and prayers headed toward this student, his family and friends and all those involved in this accident including our wonderful first responders and police department members. If you or one of your children needs to talk with someone because of the effect this accident is having on you or them please reach out to the school by calling or texting 315-244-7748 and we will work to gather together and work through the difficulties you may be experiencing.
